    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c7ef4e9f_c33908a9",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/appengine/static/common/js/build.js",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 146,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-03T20:21:58Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "this isn\u0027t responsive, i.e. if we resize the window, it is not updated.\n\nalso these kinds of things are usually done with css media queries.\n\ni think it is ok to always have tabs. They are useful even with a wide screen",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 146,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 146,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "caab85964662c83f66e4bbcb0dd2739322cf5583",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "71e2a570_eebacbf2",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/appengine/static/common/js/build.js",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 146,
      "author": {
        "id": 1297361
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-04T00:42:49Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I could watch the window size and switch when they pass the threshold.\n\nOr I could continue to draw based on the initial page width and then add a widget to allow them to switch between narrow and wide versions. (and use a cookie to remember)\n\nNote that there are always tabs - but wide screens get two tabs with more stuff on the first tab and narrow screens get four tabs with everything separated out.\n\nI\u0027m not sure that css and media queries can handle this as this approach is using jquery javascript to move divs into different tabs / add / remove tabs.\n\nAny preference amongst the ideas here?",
      "parentUuid": "c7ef4e9f_c33908a9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 146,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 146,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "caab85964662c83f66e4bbcb0dd2739322cf5583",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9f23745b_471a8114",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/appengine/static/common/js/build.js",
        "patchSetId": 10
      },
      "lineNbr": 146,
      "author": {
        "id": 1002080
      },
      "writtenOn": "2018-12-04T01:17:48Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "People have complained about too much whitespace on wide screens before, and I think people will complain if we hide things behind tabs when there is extra screen real-estate that should be used.\n\nBut media queries are generally better than JS DOM manipulation.  I dug around a bit and it looks like you can actually make tabs using pure CSS (using HTML5 grid layout):\nexample: https://codepen.io/Kseso/pen/evqBRL\nWith this, it would be possible to do goWideMode() with only CSS and media queries.",
      "parentUuid": "c7ef4e9f_c33908a9",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 146,
        "startChar": 1,
        "endLine": 146,
        "endChar": 33
      },
      "revId": "caab85964662c83f66e4bbcb0dd2739322cf5583",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d93eca61_ab111b0a",
        "filename": "milo/frontend/appengine/static/common/js/build.js",
